      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you explain the molecular mechanism of action for Ibuprofen? I'm trying to understand how it actually works as an NSAID at the enzyme level. thanks.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ibuprofen, a common NSAID, works by inhibiting the enzyme cyclooxygenase (COX). COX exists in two forms, COX-1 and COX-2, which are involved in the production of prostaglandins. Prostaglandins are substances that mediate inflammation, pain, and fever. Ibuprofen selectively inhibits COX-2, reducing the production of prostaglandins and thereby alleviating pain and inflammation. However, since COX-1 also plays a role in protecting the stomach lining, the inhibition of COX-1 by ibuprofen can lead to gastrointestinal side effects.",
